rectory |year=2002 |publisher=Thomas Brothers |page=xvi |isbn=978-1-58174-339-5}}</ref>}} is a [[neighborhood]] on the [[Los Angeles Westside|Westside of Los Angeles, California]], in the foothills of the [[Santa Monica Mountains]].  Founded in 1923, it is the home of The [[Hannah Carter Japanese Garden]] and the [[American Jewish University]].  \n\n==History==\n[[File:Entrance_to_Bel-Air,_Los_Angeles,_1923.jpg|thumb|right|<center>Entrance to Bel-Air, 1923</center>]]\nThe community was founded in 1923 by [[Alphonzo Bell]]. Bell owned farm property in [[Santa Fe Springs, California]], where oil was discovered. He bought a large ranch with a home on what is now Bel Air Road. He subdivided and developed the property with large residential lots, with work on the master plan led by the landscape architect [[Mark Daniels]].<ref name=thompson>{{cite web |last=Thompson |first=Daniella |url=http://berkeleyheritage.com/eastbay_then-now/mark_daniels.html |title=Mark Daniels excelled in developing and marketing scenic beauty |website=Berkeley Architectural Heritage Association |date=April 18, 2007}}</ref> He also built the [[Bel-Air Bay Club]] in [[Pacific Palisades, Los Angeles| Pacific Palisades]] and the [[Bel-Air Country Club]]. His wife chose Italian names for the streets. She also founded the Bel-Air Garden Club in 1931.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://sites.google.com/site/belaironline/history-of-bel-air |title=History of Bel-Air |work=Bel-Air Association |access-date=November 14, 2013 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140223140013/https://sites.google.com/site/belaironline/history-of-bel-air |archive-date=February 23, 2014}}</ref>\n\nTogether with [[Beverly Hills, California|Beverly Hills]] and [[Holmby Hills]], Bel Air forms the [[Platinum Triangle, Los Angeles|Platinum Triangle]] of Los Angeles neighborhoods.<ref>{{cite news |first=Annette |last=Haddad |url=http://articles.latimes.com/2007/jul/07/business/fi-platinum7 |title=No housing slump for super-rich \u2013 sales and prices have never been better in the Platinum Triangle |newspaper=[[Los Angeles Times]] |date=July 7, 2007}}</ref>\n\n===Fires===\n{{Main article|Bel Air Fire}}\n{{See also|Skirball Fire}}\nOn November 6, 1961, a fire ignited and devastated the community of Bel Air, destroying 484 homes in the area.{{r|LAT 2005/mar/06}} On December 6, 2017, a fire started by a homeless encampment burned in the same area, destroying six homes.\n\n==Geography==\nBel Air is situated about {{convert|12|mi|km}} west of [[Downtown Los Angeles]]<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.mapquest.com/directions/main.adp?go=1&do=nw&rmm=1&un=m&cl=EN&qq=m4ZeC4eEaUie4RjX08DrqgYWMk03zWx96Z9ral7TljVvacfcDMHtdOIztwOnN%252boXzCARpe3YHXygs%252fsqxBopNzwQ2TWwtkg11eDVsOSmt4kOAIAa1%252boQgKAhdGlLibbWvNCrZ8Y5OFdkSYjisL2Yp7RsEtDJpQQHl9%252fO1dR59nXdbzq9wKtZ%252bcQnW8kjvW6X&ct=NA&rsres=1&1y=US&1ffi=&1l=&1g=&1pl=&1v=&1n=&1pn=&1a=&1c=Los+Angeles&1s=CA&1z=&panelbtn=1&2y=US&2ffi=&2l=&2g=&2pl=&2v=&2n=&2pn=&2a=&2c=Bel+Air&2s=CA&2z= |title=Driving Directions from Los Angeles, CA to Bel Air, CA |website=Mapquest.com |accessdate=January 14, 2013}}</ref> and includes some of the foothills of the [[Santa Monica Mountains]]. It lies across [[Sunset Boulevard]] from the northern edge of the main campus of the [[University of California, Los Angeles]]. At the heart of the community sits the [[Bel-Air Country Club]] and the [[Hotel Bel-Air]].{{citation needed|date=November 2015}}\n\nAlong with [[Beverly Hills]] and the Los Angeles community of [[Brentwood, Los Angeles|Brentwood]], Bel Air is part of a high-priced area on the Westside known as the \"three Bs.\"<ref name=BDSp347>{{cite book |first1=Mehdi |last1=Bozorgmehr |first2=Claudia |last2=Der-Martirosian |first3=Georges |last3=Sabagh |chapter=Middle Easterners: A New Kind of Immigrant |editor-first1=Roger |editor-last1=Waldinger |editor-first2=Mehdi |editor-last2=Bozorgmehr |title=Ethnic Los Angeles |publisher=[[Russell Sage Foundation]] |date=December 5, 1996 |isbn=978-1-61044-547-4 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=zwwXAwAAQBAJ&pg=PA347 |page=347 |quote=...in Beverly Hills, Bel Air, and Brentwood, known in local parlance as 'the three Bs.'}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Melton |first=Mary |url=http://articles.latimes.com/1996-08-25/magazine/tm-37374_1_movie-star-map |title=The Stars of Star Maps |newspaper=[[Los Angeles Times]] |date=August 25, 1996 |quote=Each map tends to cover the 'three Bs': Brentwood, Bel-Air and Beverly Hills. A few toss in a Malibu sidebar.}}</ref> <ref>{{cite news |last=Myers |first=David W. |url=http://articles.latimes.com/1993-05-28/business/fi-40878_1_home-prices |title=A Sad Westside Story : Home Prices Have Declined as Much as 50% Since the 1980s |newspaper=Los Angeles Times |date=May 28, 1993 |accessdate=July 4, 2014 |quote=But, as Meyer's case suggests, nowhere have those losses been as dramatic as the high-priced area on the Westside known as the 'three Bs' \u2013 Brentwood, Bel-Air and Beverly Hills.}}</ref>\n\n===Climate===\nThis region experiences warm and dry summers.  According to the [[K\u00f6ppen Climate Classification]] system, Bel Air has a [[Mediterranean climate#Warm-summer Mediterranean climate|warm-summer Mediterranean climate]], abbreviated \"Csb\" on climate maps.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.weatherbase.com/weather/weather-summary.php3?s=110024&cityname=Bel+Air%2C+California%2C+United+States+of+America&units= |title=Climate Summary for Bel Air, California |website=Weatherbase.com |accessdate=September 12, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Demographics==\nThe 2000 U.S. census counted 7,691 residents in the {{convert|6.37|sqmi|adj=on}} Bel Air neighborhood; with {{convert|1207|/sqmi}} it has among the lowest [[population densities]] for the city and the county. In 2008, the city estimated that the population had increased to 8,253.\n\nIn 2000 the median age for residents was 46, which was high for city and county neighborhoods. The percentages of residents aged 50 and older was among the county's highest.<ref name=MappingLABelAir>{{cite web|url=http://projects.latimes.com/mapping-la/neighborhoods/neighborhood/bel-air|title=Bel-Air|website=Mapping L.A.|publisher=Los Angeles Times|accessdate=October 31, 2015}}</ref>\n\nThe median yearly household income in 2008 was $207,938, the highest figure for any [[neighborhood]] or [[city]] in Los Angeles County. Renters occupied 14.5% of the housing stock, and house- or apartment-owners held 85.5%. The average household size of 2.4 people was considered typical for Los Angeles.<ref name=MappingLABelAir/>\n\nThe 4.1% of families headed by single parents was considered low for city and county neighborhoods. The percentages of married people in Bel Air were among the county's highest\u201466.0% for men and 65.7% for women. There were 808 veterans, or 12.9% of the population.<ref name=MappingLABelAir/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://maps.latimes.com/neighborhoods/veterans/neighborhood/list/|title=Veterans Ranking |website=Mapping L.A.|publisher=Los Angeles Times|accessdate=October 31, 2015}}</ref>\n\nThe neighborhood was considered \"not especially diverse\" ethnically<ref>{{cite web|url=http://maps.latimes.com/neighborhoods/diversity/neighborhood/list|title=Diversity|website=Mapping L.A.|publisher=Los Angeles Times|quote=The diversity index measures the probability that any two residents, chosen at random, would be of different ethnicities. If all residents are of the same ethnic group it's zero. If half are from one group and half from another it's .50.\" |accessdate=October 31, 2015}}</ref> within Los Angeles, with a relatively high percentage of white people. The breakdown was [[Non-Hispanic Whites|whites]], 83.0%; [[Asian American|Asians]], 8.2%; [[Hispanic and Latino Americans|Latinos]], 4.6%; [[African American|blacks]], 0.9%; and others, 3.2%. Iran (26.1%) and South Africa (8.2%) were the most common places of birth for the 24.1% of the residents who were born abroad\u2014which was an average percentage for Los Angeles as a whole.<ref name=MappingLABelAir/>\n\n===Neighborhoods===\nOf several entrances, there are two main ones: (1) the [[East Gate Bel Air, Los Angeles|East Gate]] at [[Beverly Glen Boulevard|Beverly Glen]] and [[Sunset Boulevard|Sunset]] Boulevards and (2) the West Gate at Bellagio Way and [[Sunset Boulevard]], opposite an entrance to [[UCLA]]. Bel Air is generally subdivided into three distinct neighborhoods: [[East Gate Bel Air, Los Angeles|East Gate Old Bel Air]], West Gate Bel Air, and Upper Bel Air.{{r|LAT 2005/mar/06}}{{citation needed|date=November 2015}}\n\nBel Air Estates, the original subdivision of the Bel Air community, is generally bounded by Nimes Road to the north, Sunset Boulevard to the south, Beverly Glen Boulevard to the east and both sides of Bel Air Road to the west.<ref>[http://www.preservation.lacity.org/files/Bel%20Air%20-Beverly%20Crest%20Districts.pdf SurveyLA: Bel Air - Beverly Crest Report Historic Districts, Planning Districts and Multi-Property Resources \u2013 12/05/13]</ref>\n\n==Attractions==\nThe [[Hannah Carter Japanese Garden]] is located in Bel Air. It was inspired by the gardens of [[Kyoto]]. Many structures in the garden\u2014the main gate, garden house, bridges, and shrine\u2014were built in [[Japan]] and reassembled here. Antique stone carvings, water basins and lanterns, as well as the five-tiered [[pagoda]], and key symbolic rocks are also from Japan.<ref name=\"LAT 20150930\">{{cite news |url=http://www.latimes.com/local/lanow/la-me-ln-ucla-and-carter-heirs-settle-suit-over-japanese-garden-20150930-story.html |title=UCLA and Hannah Carter heirs settle suit over Japanese garden in Bel-Air |first=Martha |last=Groves |newspaper=[[Los Angeles Times]]|date=September 30, 2015 |access-date=April 17, 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Government and infrastructure==\nThe [[Los Angeles County Department of Health Services]] SPA 5 West Area Health Office serves Bel Air.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://publichealth.lacounty.gov/phcommon/public/aboutus/aboutdisplay.cfm?ou=ph&prog=chs&unit=spa5 |title=About Us |website=[[Los Angeles County Department of Health Services]] |accessdate=March 18, 2010}}</ref>\n\nIt lies within the 5th city council district, represented by [[Paul Koretz]].  It is located in the 90077 (Bel Air Estates & Beverly Glen) ZIP code, which is part of the city of Los Angeles. [[Stone Canyon Reservoir]] lies in the northeastern part of Bel Air. Established in 1994, it serves around 500,000 people. The Bel Air Association has been operational since 1942, dedicated to preserving the aesthetic appearance of the residential community. The Bel Air Association is located at the entrance of the East Gate of Bel Air at 100 Bel Air Road.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://sites.google.com/site/belaironline/Home/about-us |title=About us |website=Bel~Air Association |\narchiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100409113136/http://sites.google.com/site/belaironline/Home/about-us |archivedate=April 9, 2010}}</ref>\n\n==Emergency services==\n===Fire services===\n[[Los Angeles Fire Department]] Station 71 is in the area.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.lafd.org/fs71.htm |title=Fire Station 71 |website=[[Los Angeles Fire Department]] |accessdate=October 31, 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Police services===\nThe [[Los Angeles Police Department]] operates the West Los Angeles Community Police Station at 1663 Butler Avenue, 90025, serving the neighborhood.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.lapdonline.org/west_la_community_police_station |title=West LA Community Police Station |website=Los Angeles Police Department |accessdate=October 31, 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Education==\n[[File:American Jewish University, Bel Air, California.JPG|thumb|right|The [[American Jewish University]], located in the Bel Air Casiano neighborhood]]\nAlmost two-thirds (66.1%) of Bel Air residents aged 25 and older had earned a [[four-year degree]] by 2000, a high percentage for the city and the county. The percentages of residents in that age range with a [[bachelor's degree]] or greater were high for the county.<ref name=MappingLABelAir/> The community is within the [[Los Angeles Unified School District]]. The area is within Board District 4.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.lausd.k12.ca.us/lausd/board/secretary/BoardDistrictMaps/2007-08%20Board%20District%204.pdf |title=Board District 4 Map |website=[[Los Angeles Unified School District]] |accessdate=November 24, 2008}}</ref> As of 2009, Steve Zimmer represented the district.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.laschoolboard.org |title=Board Members |website=Los Angeles Unified School District |accessdate=September 16, 2009}}</ref>\n\n===Schools===\nThe schools within Bel Air are as follows:<ref name=MappingLABelairSchools>{{cite web |url=http://projects.latimes.com/mapping-la/neighborhoods/neighborhood/bel-air/schools/ |title=Bel-Air Schools |website=Mapping L.A. |publisher=Los Angeles Times |accessdate=October 31, 2015}}</ref>\n\n====Public====\n* Roscomare Road Elementary School, 2425 Roscomare Road<ref name=Savage>{{cite news |last=Savage |first=David G. |url=https://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/latimes/access/663790622.html?dids=663790622:663790622&FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:AI&type=historic&date=Apr+11%2C+1982&author=&pub=Los+Angeles+Times&desc=Many+Minority+Students+Back+in+Their+Old+Schools&pqatl=google |title=Many Minority Students Back in Their Old Schools |newspaper=[[Los Angeles Times]] |date=April 11, 1982 |accessdate=March 23, 2010 |quote=...a bright and talkative black girl, rode a school bus from her home west of down-town Los Angeles to Roscomare Road Elementary School in the hills of Bel Air.}}</ref>\n* Community Magnet Charter Elementary School, 11301 Bellagio Road. {{Asof|2010}}, because the school's points-based admissions system does not favor area residents, children living in Bel Air generally do not attend the school.<ref name=\"Guzman\">{{cite web |last=Guzman |first=Stephanie |url=http://www.neontommy.com/news/2010/08/look-la-unified-community-magnet |title=A Look Into L.A. Unified: Community Magnet |website=Neon Tommy (Annenberg Digital News) |publisher=[[University of Southern California]] Annenberg School for Communication and Journalism |date=August 15, 2010 |accessdate=January 15, 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120506002546/http://www.neontommy.com/news/2010/08/look-la-unified-community-magnet |archive-date=May 6, 2012 |url-status=dead }}</ref> It is located in the former Bellagio Road School campus.<ref name=\"Bellagiomovemeeting\">{{cite web |url=http://www.lausd.k12.ca.us/Community_EL/Minutes/CC7-8-02.pdf |title=Community School Proposed Relocation to Bellagio Road School Community Meeting |website=Community Magnet School |date=July 8, 2002 |accessdate=January 15, 2012}}</ref>\n\nRoscomare Road and Warner Avenue Elementary School in [[Westwood, Los Angeles, California|Westwood]] are the zoned elementary schools serving Bel Air.<ref name=Savage/><ref name=\"LAT 2005/mar/06\">{{cite news |last=Lesel |first=Helene |title=A Part of the City, Yet Apart from it Too |newspaper=[[Los Angeles Times]] |date=March 6, 2005 |url=http://articles.latimes.com/2005/mar/06/realestate/re-guide6 |access-date=March 23, 2010}}</ref> Bel Air is within the attendance boundaries of [[Emerson Middle School (Los Angeles, California)|Emerson Middle School]] in Westwood and [[University High School (Los Angeles, California)|University High School, West Los Angeles]].{{r|LAT 2005/mar/06}}\n\nIn April 1983 an advisory committee of the LAUSD recommended closing eight LAUSD schools, including Bellagio Road School. The committee did not target Fairburn Avenue School in Westwood, as a way of allowing it to preserve its ethnic balance, and so it can take children from Bellagio Road in the event that it closed.<ref>{{cite news |last=Faris |first=Gerald |url=https://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/latimes/access/667529832.html?dids=667529832:667529832&FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:AI&type=historic&date=Apr+17%2C+1983&author=&pub=Los+Angeles+Times&desc=Closing+of+8+Schools+Recommended%2C+One+Near+Airport&pqatl=google |title=Closing of 8 Schools Recommended, One Near Airport |newspaper=Los Angeles Times |date=April 17, 1983 |accessdate=January 16, 2012}}</ref> In August 1983 the board publicly considered closing Bellagio, which had 240 students at the time.<ref>{{cite news |last=Pool |first=Bob |url=https://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/latimes/access/668614182.html?dids=668614182:668614182&FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:AI&type=historic&date=Aug+07%2C+1983&author=&pub=Los+Angeles+Times&desc=Board+to+Consider+Closing+4+More+Valley+Schools&pqatl=google |title=Board to Consider Closing 4 More Valley Schools |date=August 7, 1983 |newspaper=Los Angeles Times |accessdate=January 16, 2012}}</ref> The school's enrollment had been decreasing. In May 1983 the board voted to keep the school open. In February 1984, after the composition of the board had changed, the board voted to close the Bellagio Road School.<ref>{{cite news |last=Savage |first=David G. |url=https://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/latimes/access/671185632.html?dids=671185632:671185632&FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:AI&type=historic&date=Feb+07%2C+1984&author=&pub=Los+Angeles+Times&desc=L.A.+Board+to+Close+5+More+Schools&pqatl=google |title=L.A. Board to Close 5 More Schools |newspaper=Los Angeles Times |date=February 7, 1984 |accessdate=January 16, 2012}}</ref>\n\nBel Air previously housed the Bellagio Road Newcomer School, a 3rd\u20138th grade school for newly arrived immigrants. In 2002 it had 390 students from Armenia, China, El Salvador, Guatemala, Korea, Russia, and other countries.<ref name=\"Helfand2\">{{cite news |last1=Helfand |first1=Duke |first2=Erika |last2=Hayasaki |title=$459 Million in Cuts Are Considered for Fiscally Strapped L.A. Schools |newspaper=Los Angeles Times |date=April 26, 2002 |url=http://articles.latimes.com/2002/apr/26/local/me-lausd26/2 |page=2 |accessdate=January 16, 2012}}</ref> This program was housed in the former Bellagio Road school.<ref>{{cite news |last=Shuster |first=Beth |url=http://nl.newsbank.com/nl-search/we/Archives?p_product=LA&p_theme=la&p_action=search&p_maxdocs=200&p_topdoc=1&p_text_direct-0=0EF518DC03803D6F&p_field_direct-0=document_id&p_perpage=10&p_sort=YMD_date:D&s_trackval=GooglePM |title=Pilot Program Urged For 8 Elementary Schools |newspaper=[[Los Angeles Daily News]] |date=May 13, 1988 |accessdate=January 16, 2012}}</ref>\n\n====Private====\n* [[Marymount High School]], 10643 Sunset Boulevard\n* [[Stephen S. Wise Temple]] Elementary School/[[Milken Community Schools]], [[K\u201312]], 15500 Stephen S. Wise Drive\n* [[John Thomas Dye School]],  K\u20136,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.belaironline.org/SubPageContent.asp?ID=54 |title=The John Thomas Dye School |website=Bel Air Association |access-date=January 10, 2008 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081030095718/http://www.belaironline.org/SubPageContent.asp?ID=54 |archive-date=October 30, 2008 |url-status=dead }}</ref> 11414 Chalon Road\n* [[The Mirman School]]<ref name=WooBrightMinds>{{cite news |url=http://articles.latimes.com/2000/nov/22/news/cl-55461 |title=Where Bright Minds Can Shine |first=Elaine |last=Woo |newspaper=Los Angeles Times |date=November 22, 2000}}</ref>\n* [[The Westland School (Los Angeles)|Westland School]], 16200 Mulholland Drive, was founded in 1949. It moved to its current location in 1965, becoming the first school to locate in what has now developed into a major 'institutional corridor' in the area of the [[Sepulveda Pass]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://articles.latimes.com/1995-05-21/local/me-4455_1_sepulveda-pass |title=Culture Shock Many Object to the Growing Sprawl of Institutions Atop Sepulveda Pass |first=Jon D. |last=Markman |newspaper=Los Angeles Times |date=May 21, 1995 |accessdate=October 19, 2013}}</ref>\n\n====University====\nBel Air is home to the [[American Jewish University]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://articles.latimes.com/2007/mar/22/local/me-briefs22.2 |title=Two Jewish educational institutes are merging |newspaper=Los Angeles Times |date=March 22, 2007}}</ref>\n\n==In popular culture==\nTelevision shows and films have been filmed in Bel Air, or are said to take place in the community. Exterior shots for the ''[[Beverly Hillbillies]]'' were shot in and around 750 Bel Air Road,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.tvacres.com/locations.htm |title=Real Estate: TV Show Buildings At A Glance |website=TV Acres |accessdate=January 14, 2013 |archive-url=https://archive.today/20120604183029/http://www.tvacres.com/locations.htm |archive-date=June 4, 2012 |url-status=dead }}</ref> built by Lynn Atkinson (and later sold to hotelier [[Arnold Kirkeby]] after Atkinson's wife refused to move into a house she thought too ostentatious). After the exterior shooting was completed, the residents of that address forbade any more filming, as passers-by would wander onto the property and ask to see 'Granny'.\n\nExterior scenes from films such as ''[[Get Shorty]]'' have also been filmed in the area.{{citation needed|date=February 2008}} Several episodes of the television show ''[[The Rockford Files]]'' were filmed in Bel Air.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://maps.google.com/maps?q=Bel+Air+Road,+Los+Angeles,+CA&hl=en&ll=34.083256,-118.440197&spn=0.000212,0.000627&sll=34.112568,-118.479331&sspn=0.010571,0.020063&vpsrc=6&gl=us&hnear=Bel+Air+Rd,+Los+Angeles,+California&t=h&z=21&layer=c&cbll=34.083256,-118.440197&panoid=tnQVyC_CYbzzsU9qY996qg&cbp=12,349.47,,0,-4.43|title=Display of estate used in several episodes|website=Google Maps}}</ref>\n\nThe television sitcom ''[[The Fresh Prince of Bel-Air]]'' was set in the neighborhood, although the exterior shots used were filmed in nearby [[Brentwood, Los Angeles|Brentwood]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.iamnotastalker.com/2008/05/22/fresh-prince-house-for-real-this-time|title=Fresh Prince House \u2013 For Real This Time!|website=Iamnotastalker.com|date=May 22, 2008|accessdate=January 14, 2013}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Bel Air Film Festival]], first held in 2008,<ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://www.variety.com/blog/1390000339-34730.html|magazine=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|title=Bel Air gets a fest|first=Michael|last=Jones|date=October 21, 2008 |accessdate=July 23, 2010}}</ref> is an annual international [[film festival]] held in Bel Air and the Los Angeles area.\n\n==Notable people==\n\n* [[Jennifer Aniston]], actress<ref>{{cite web |title=Jennifer Aniston buys big digs in Bel Air |website=Real Estalker |url=http://realestalker.blogspot.com/2012/01/jennifer-aniston-buys-big-digs-in-bel.html |accessdate=April 4, 2014}}</ref>\n* [[Warner Baxter]], actor<ref>{{cite web |title=Homes of the Western Stars (A-B) |url=https://stevesomething.wordpress.com/2011/05/24/homes-of-the-western-stars-a-b/ |website=Charles Starrett \u2013 One Fan's Journey |accessdate=January 2, 2016 |first=Bob |last=Siler}}</ref>\n* [[Arie Belldegrun|Arie]] and [[Rebecka Belldegrun]], doctors<ref>{{cite news|url=https://labusinessjournal.com/news/2018/mar/23/professor-entrepreneur-arie-belldegrun-bhof/|title=Professor as Entrepreneur: UCLA's Belldegrun on to Next Biopharma Enterprise|newspaper=[[Los Angeles Business Journal]]|year=2018}}</ref>\n* [[Jack Benny]], comedian\n* [[Beyonc\u00e9]], singer-songwriter, actress<ref name=JayZandBeyoncenewmansion>{{cite news|url=http://www.latimes.com/business/realestate/hot-property/la-fi-hp-hotprop-20170826-story.html|title=Jay-Z and Beyonc\u00e9 put down roots in L.A. with $88-million splash|author=NEAL J. LEITEREG, LAUREN BEALE and JACK FLEMMING|date=August 26, 2017|work=[[Los Angeles Times]]}}</ref>\n* [[Wilt Chamberlain]], Basketball Hall of Fame inductee<ref name=berg>{{cite web |title=Former home of Wilt Chamberlain is up for sale |url=http://www.bergproperties.com/blog/former-home-of-wilt-chamberlain-is-up-for-sale |website=Berg Properties |date=March 9, 2007}}</ref>\n* [[John Gilbert (actor)|John Gilbert]], actor<ref>{{cite news |title=John Gilbert, film actor, dies of heart attack |newspaper=[[Reading Eagle]] |date=January 9, 1936 |page=13 |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1955&dat=19360109&id=xLEhAAAAIBAJ&sjid=cJsFAAAAIBAJ&pg=4355,1560527&hl=en |via=Google News |accessdate=January 6, 2016}}</ref>\n* [[Alfred Hitchcock]], film director<ref name=\"SantaCruzInspiration\">{{cite web |title=Local Inspiration for Movie Classics: Hitchcock had Link to Santa Cruz |website=Santa Cruz Public Libraries |url=http://www.santacruzpl.org/history/films/hitch.shtml |accessdate=March 4, 2008 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070905101712/http://www.santacruzpl.org/history/films/hitch.shtml |archivedate=September 5, 2007}}</ref>\n* [[Jay-Z]], rapper<ref name=\"JayZandBeyoncenewmansion\" />\n* [[Mary Livingstone]], actress and comedian\n* [[Joni Mitchell]], singer-songwriter<ref>{{cite magazine |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/joni-mitchell-defends-herself-19790726 |title=Joni Mitchell Defends Herself |first=Cameron |last=Crowe |authorlink=Cameron Crowe |date=July 26, 1979 |magazine=[[Rolling Stone]] |accessdate=September 12, 2017}}</ref>\n* [[Steven Mnuchin]], 77th United States secretary of the treasury<ref>{{cite web\n|url=https://abc7.com/manure-filled-package-sent-to-steve-mnuchins-bel-air-home/2817980/\n|title=Manure-filled package sent to Treasury Secretary Steve Mnuchin sends bomb squad to Bel Air\n|publisher=[[KABC-TV|ABC 7]]\n|year=2017\n|accessdate=2019-10-25\n}}</ref>\n* [[Elon Musk]], entrepreneur, investor and engineer<ref>{{cite magazine |last=Musk |first=Justine |url=http://www.marieclaire.com/sex-love/relationship-issues/millionaire-starter-wife |title='I Was a Starter Wife': Inside America's Messiest Divorce |magazine=[[Marie Claire]] |date=September 10, 2010 |accessdate=September 24, 2011}}</ref>\n* [[Leonard Nimoy]], actor, film director, poet, singer and photographer<ref name=\"NYT-20150227\">{{cite news |last=Heffernan |first=Virginia |title=Leonard Nimoy, Spock of 'Star Trek', Dies at 83 |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/02/27/arts/television/leonard-nimoy-spock-of-star-trek-dies-at-83.html |date=February 27, 2015 |newspaper=[[The New York Times]] |accessdate=October 31, 2015}}</ref>\n* [[Chris Paul]], basketball athlete<ref>{{cite web |title=Chris Paul Just Bought Avril Lavigne's $8.5 Million Mansion In Bel Air |first=Leah |last=Goldman |date=January 20, 2012 |website=[[Business Insider]] |url=http://www.businessinsider.com/chris-paul-house-photos-2012-1 |accessdate=April 13, 2014}}</ref>\n* President [[Ronald Reagan]] and First Lady [[Nancy Reagan]]<ref>{{cite news |last=Sanchez |first=Rene |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=x7caAAAAIBAJ&sjid=JUUEAAAAIBAJ&pg=6244,3707654&dq=bel-air+reagan+decades&hl=en |title=Presidential library, Bel Air streets become centers for grieving |newspaper=[[Milwaukee Journal Sentinel]] |date=June 6, 2004 |page=13A |accessdate=January 16, 2012}}</ref>\n* [[Naty Saidoff]], diamond dealer, real estate investor,  founding member of the [[Israeli-American Council]]<ref>{{cite news\n|url=http://www.ladowntownnews.com/news/downtown-s-quiet-bel-air-buyer/article_5eb172d8-dac7-11e2-90a6-0019bb2963f4.html\n|title=Downtown's Quiet Bel Air Buyer\n|newspaper=[[Los Angeles Downtown News]]\n|year=2013\n|accessdate=2019-10-25\n}}</ref>\n* [[Darren Star]], show and movie producer, writer<ref name=\"rus\">{{cite magazine |last=Mayer |first=Rus |url=http://www.architecturaldigest.com/celebrity-homes/2012/darren-star-waldo-fernandez-hollywood-home-article |title=TV Mogul Darren Star's Art-Filled Bel Air Home |date=March 2012 |magazine=[[Architectural Digest]]}}</ref>\n* [[Elizabeth Taylor]], actress<ref>{{cite web |last=Brenoff |first=Ann |url=http://realestate.aol.com/blog/2011/05/20/liz-taylors-bel-air-home-hits-market-at-8-6-million |title=Liz Taylor's Bel-Air Home Hits Market at $8.6 Million |website=AOL Real Estate |date=May 20, 2011 |accessdate=January 14, 2013}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of districts and neighborhoods in Los Angeles]]\n* [[List of largest houses in the Los Angeles Metropolitan Area]]\n\n==Footnotes==\n{{reflist|group=fn}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|refs=\n}}\n\n{{Geographic Location 2\n|Center    = Bel Air\n|North     = [[Sherman Oaks, California|Sherman Oaks]]\n|Northeast = [[Studio City, Los Angeles|Studio City]]\n|East      = [[Beverly Glen, Los Angeles|Beverly Glen]]\n|ENE       =\n|Southeast = [[Los Angeles Country Club]] and [[Beverly Hills, California|Beverly Hills]]\n|Southwest = [[Santa Monica, California]]\n|South     = [[University of California, Los Angeles|UCLA]] and [[Westwood, Los Angeles|Westwood Village]]\n|WSW       =\n|West      = [[Brentwood, Los Angeles]] and [[Interstate 405 (California)|Interstate 405]]\n|WNW       =\n|Northwest =[[Encino, California]] and [[Santa Monica Mountains]]\n}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Bel Air}}\n\n{{Coord|34.08333|-118.44778|type:city_region:US|format=dms|display=title}}\n{{Bel Air, Los Angeles}}\n{{Los Angeles Westside}}\n\n[[Category:1923 establishments in California]]\n[[Category:Populated places established in 1923]]\n[[Category:Bel Air, Los Angeles| ]]\n[[Category:Neighborhoods in Los Angeles]]\n[[Category:Westside (Los Angeles County)]]\n[[Category:Populated places in the Santa Monica Mountains]]\n", "name_user": "78.143.221.120", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eNotable people)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bel_Air,_Los_Angeles"}
